ce:section.ce:para:
Efficient charge transport performance is an ideal requirement for catalysts to have high activity. Therefore, the photoelectrochemistry properties of BNNR, C-BNNR and GQDs/C-BNNR heterojunctions were evaluated to facilitate the enhanced photocatalytic performance of GQDs/C-BNNR from the perspective of electron migration kinetics. The carrier separation ability of BNNR, C-BNNR and GQDs/C-BNNR heterojunctions was investigated by photoluminescence (PL) spectroscopy (Fig. 12
                     (a)). It was observed that several materials can produce emission peaks near 335 nm, and BNNR shows the highest emission peak intensity. Meanwhile, compared with C-BNNR, the addition of GQDs further reduces the PL intensity of the composites, indicating that the formation of heterojunction can significantly reduce the photogenerated carrier recombination rate, thus improving the catalytic activity. Furthermore, the time-resolved PL spectral data of the catalyst were fitted using a double exponential model to obtain its fluorescence lifetime (Fig. 12(b)). The fluorescence lifetimes of the GQDs/C-BNNR heterojunctions, especially GQDs/C-BNNR-3 (40.89 ns), are significantly larger than BNNR (21.30 ns) and C-BNNR (24.50 ns). The result demonstrates that the photoelectron lifetime of the catalyst is extended after the introduction of GQDs, which resulted the catalyst have stronger catalytic activity. Fig. 12(c)-(d) shows the photocurrent response curves and electrochemical impedance (EIS) curves of BNNR, C-BNNR and GQDs/C-BNNR heterojunctions. The stronger photocurrent intensity and smaller impedance radius of the GQDs/C-BNNR can be clearly observed, illustrating that the composites generate more photogenerated electrons under light and have a lower charge transfer resistance. The electrical properties of GQDs/C-BNNR show that a new photogenerated electron transfer path is formed. In conclusion, the results of the photoelectrochemistry properties of BNNR, C-BNNR and GQDs/C-BNNR were consistent with the photocatalytic activity test results. It indicate that the introduction of GQDs can effectively improve the charge separation efficiency of the catalyst and prolong the life of photogenerated electrons, promoting the next step of CO2 photocatalytic reduction kinetics. Finally, the possible CO2 photocatalytic reduction process on the GQDs/C-BNNR surface was inferred based on the previous measurements and analysis (Fig. 13
                     ).
